1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:This paper reports on theoretical investigations about the assumptions underlying the inverse document frequency (idf ) .
1-2:We show that an intuitive idf based probability function for the probability of a term being informative assumes disjoint document events .
1-3:By assuming documents to be independent rather than disjoint, we arrive at a Poisson based probability of being informative .
1-4:The framework is useful for understanding and deciding the parameter estimation and combination in probabilistic retrieval models .
1-5:H.3.3 [Information Search and Retrieval]: Retrieval .
2 INTRODUCTION AND BACKGROUND :
2-1:The inverse document frequency (idf ) is one of the most successful parameters for a relevance based ranking of retrieved objects .
2-2:With N being the total number of documents, and n(t) being the number of documents in which term t occurs, the idf is defined as follows: idf(t) := − log n(t) N , 0 <= idf(t) < ∞ Ranking based on the sum of the idf values of the query terms that occur in the retrieved documents works well, this has been shown in numerous applications .
2-3:Also, it is well known that the combination of a document specific term weight and idf works better than idf alone .
2-4:This approach is known as tf idf , where tf(t, d) (0 <= tf(t, d) <= 1) is the so called term frequency of term t in document d .
2-5:The idf reflects the discriminating power (informativeness) of a term, whereas the tf reflects the occurrence of a term .
2-6:The idf alone works better than the tf alone does .
2-7:An explanation might be the problem of tf with terms that occur in many documents; let us refer to those terms as noisy terms .
2-8:We use the notion of noisy terms rather than frequent terms since frequent terms leaves open whether we refer to the document frequency of a term in a collection or to the so called term frequency (also referred to as withindocument frequency) of a term in a document .
2-9:We associate noise with the document frequency of a term in a collection, and we associate occurrence with the withindocument frequency of a term .
2-10:The tf of a noisy term might be high in a document, but noisy terms are not good candidates for representing a document .
2-11:Therefore, the removal of noisy terms (known as stopword removal) is essential when applying tf .
2-12:In a tf idf approach, the removal of stopwords is conceptually obsolete, if stopwords are just words with a low idf .
2-13:From a probabilistic point of view, tf is a value with a frequency based probabilistic interpretation whereas idf has an informative rather than a probabilistic interpretation .
2-14:The missing probabilistic interpretation of idf is a problem in probabilistic retrieval models where we combine uncertain knowledge of different dimensions (e.g.: informativeness of terms, structure of documents, quality of documents, age of documents, etc.) such that a good estimate of the probability of relevance is achieved .
2-15:An intuitive solution is a normalisation of idf such that we obtain values in the interval [0; 1] .
2-16:For example, consider a normalisation based on the maximal idf value .
2-17:Let T be the set of terms occurring in a collection .
2-18:Pfreq (t is informative) := idf(t) maxidf maxidf := max({idf(t)|t ∈ T}), maxidf <= − log(1 N) minidf := min({idf(t)|t ∈ T}), minidf >= 0 minidf maxidf ≤ Pfreq (t is informative) ≤ 1.0 This frequency based probability function covers the interval [0; 1] if the minimal idf is equal to zero, which is the case if we have at least one term that occurs in all documents .
2-19:Can we interpret Pfreq , the normalised idf , as the probability that the term is informative? When investigating the probabilistic interpretation of the 227 normalised idf , we made several observations related to disjointness and independence of document events .
2-20:These observations are reported in section 3 .
2-21:We show in section 3.1 that the frequency based noise probability n(t) N used in the classic idf definition can be explained by three assumptions: binary term occurrence, constant document containment and disjointness of document containment events .
2-22:In section 3.2 we show that by assuming independence of documents, we obtain 1 − e−1 ≈ 1 − 0.37 as the upper bound of the noise probability of a term .
2-23:The value e−1 is related to the logarithm and we investigate in section 3.3 the link to information theory .
2-24:In section 4, we link the results of the previous sections to probability theory .
2-25:We show the steps from possible worlds to binomial distribution and Poisson distribution .
2-26:In section 5, we emphasise that the theoretical framework of this paper is applicable for both idf and tf .
2-27:Finally, in section 6, we base the definition of the probability of being informative on the results of the previous sections and compare frequency based and Poisson based definitions. .
3 BACKGROUND :
3-1:The relationship between frequencies, probabilities and information theory (entropy) has been the focus of many researchers .
3-2:In this background section, we focus on work that investigates the application of the Poisson distribution in IR since a main part of the work presented in this paper addresses the underlying assumptions of Poisson .
3-3:[4] proposes a 2 Poisson model that takes into account the different nature of relevant and non relevant documents, rare terms (content words) and frequent terms (noisy terms, function words, stopwords) .
3-4:[9] shows experimentally that most of the terms (words) in a collection are distributed according to a low dimension n Poisson model .
3-5:[10] uses a 2 Poisson model for including term frequency based probabilities in the probabilistic retrieval model .
3-6:The non linear scaling of the Poisson function showed significant improvement compared to a linear frequency based probability .
3-7:The Poisson model was here applied to the term frequency of a term in a document .
3-8:We will generalise the discussion by pointing out that document frequency and term frequency are dual parameters in the collection space and the document space, respectively .
3-9:Our discussion of the Poisson distribution focuses on the document frequency in a collection rather than on the term frequency in a document .
3-10:[7] and [6] address the deviation of idf and Poisson, and apply Poisson mixtures to achieve better Poisson based estimates .
3-11:The results proved again experimentally that a onedimensional Poisson does not work for rare terms, therefore Poisson mixtures and additional parameters are proposed .
3-12:[3], section 3.3, illustrates and summarises comprehensively the relationships between frequencies, probabilities and Poisson .
3-13:Different definitions of idf are put into context and a notion of noise is defined, where noise is viewed as the complement of idf .
3-14:We use in our paper a different notion of noise: we consider a frequency based noise that corresponds to the document frequency, and we consider a term noise that is based on the independence of document events .
3-15:[11], [12], [8] and [1] link frequencies and probability estimation to information theory .
3-16:[12] establishes a framework in which information retrieval models are formalised based on probabilistic inference .
3-17:A key component is the use of a space of disjoint events, where the framework mainly uses terms as disjoint events .
3-18:The probability of being informative defined in our paper can be viewed as the probability of the disjoint terms in the term space of [12] .
3-19:[8] address entropy and bibliometric distributions .
3-20:Entropy is maximal if all events are equiprobable and the frequency based Lotka law (N iλ is the number of scientists that have written i publications, where N and λ are distribution parameters), Zipf and the Pareto distribution are related .
3-21:The Pareto distribution is the continuous case of the Lotka and Lotka and Zipf show equivalences .
3-22:The Pareto distribution is used by [2] for term frequency normalisation .
3-23:The Pareto distribution compares to the Poisson distribution in the sense that Pareto is fat tailed, i .
3-24:e .
3-25:Pareto assigns larger probabilities to large numbers of events than Poisson distributions do .
3-26:This makes Pareto interesting since Poisson is felt to be too radical on frequent events .
3-27:We restrict in this paper to the discussion of Poisson, however, our results show that indeed a smoother distribution than Poisson promises to be a good candidate for improving the estimation of probabilities in information retrieval .
3-28:[1] establishes a theoretical link between tf idf and information theory and the theoretical research on the meaning of tf idf clarifies the statistical model on which the different measures are commonly based .
3-29:This motivation matches the motivation of our paper: We investigate theoretically the assumptions of classical idf and Poisson for a better understanding of parameter estimation and combination. .
