7-23:This radical behaviour can be smoothened by using a multi dimensional Poisson distribution .
7-24:Figure 1 shows a Poisson noise based on a two dimensional Poisson: poisson(k, λ1, λ2) := π · e−λ1 · λk 1 k! + (1 − π) · e−λ2 · λk 2 k! The two dimensional Poisson shows a plateau between λ1 = 1000 and λ2 = 2000, we used here π = 0.5 .
7-25:The idea behind this setting is that terms that occur in less than 1000 documents are considered to be not noisy (i.e .
7-26:they are informative), that terms between 1000 and 2000 are half noisy, and that terms with more than 2000 are definitely noisy .
7-27:For the informativeness, we observe that the radical behaviour of Poisson is preserved .
7-28:The plateau here is approximately at 1 6, and it is important to realise that this plateau is not obtained with the multi dimensional Poisson noise using π = 0.5 .
7-29:The logarithm of the noise is normalised by the logarithm of a very small number, namely 0.5 · e−1000 + 0.5 · e−2000 .
7-30:That is why the informativeness will be only close to one for very little noise, whereas for a bit of noise, informativeness will drop to zero .
7-31:This effect can be controlled by using small values for π such that the noise in the interval [λ1; λ2] is still very little .
