7-40:In conclusion, we have seen that the Poisson based definition provides more control and parameter possibilities than 233 the frequency based definition does .
7-41:Whereas more control and parameter promises to be positive for the personalisation of retrieval systems, it bears at the same time the danger of just too many parameters .
7-42:The framework presented in this paper raises the awareness about the probabilistic and information theoretic meanings of the parameters .
7-43:The parallel definitions of the frequency based probability and the Poisson based probability of being informative made the underlying assumptions explicit .
7-44:The frequency based probability can be explained by binary occurrence, constant containment and disjointness of documents .
7-45:Independence of documents leads to Poisson, where we have to be aware that Poisson approximates the probability of a disjunction for a large number of events, but not for a small number .
7-46:This theoretical result explains why experimental investigations on Poisson (see [7]) show that a Poisson estimation does work better for frequent (bad, noisy) terms than for rare (good, informative) terms .
7-47:In addition to the collection wide parameter setting, the framework presented here allows for document dependent settings, as explained for the independence probability .
7-48:This is in particular interesting for heterogeneous and structured collections, since documents are different in nature (size, quality, root document, sub document), and therefore, binary occurrence and constant containment are less appropriate than in relatively homogeneous collections. .
8-1:The definition of the probability of being informative transforms the informative interpretation of the idf into a probabilistic interpretation, and we can use the idf based probability in probabilistic retrieval approaches
8-2:We showed that the classical definition of the noise (document frequency) in the inverse document frequency can be explained by three assumptions: the term within document occurrence probability is binary, the document containment probability is constant, and the document containment events are disjoint
8-3:By explicitly and mathematically formulating the assumptions, we showed that the classical definition of idf does not take into account parameters such as the different nature (size, quality, structure, etc.) of documents in a collection, or the different nature of terms (coverage, importance, position, etc.) in a document
8-4:We discussed that the absence of those parameters is compensated by a leverage effect of the within document term occurrence probability and the document containment probability
8-5:By applying an independence rather a disjointness assumption for the document containment, we could establish a link between the noise probability (term occurrence in a collection), information theory and Poisson
8-6:From the frequency based and the Poisson based probabilities of being noisy, we derived the frequency based and Poisson based probabilities of being informative
8-7:The frequency based probability is relatively smooth whereas the Poisson probability is radical in distinguishing between noisy or not noisy, and informative or not informative, respectively
8-8:We showed how to smoothen the radical behaviour of Poisson with a multidimensional Poisson
8-9:The explicit and mathematical formulation of idf  and Poisson assumptions is the main result of this paper
8-10:Also, the paper emphasises the duality of idf and tf , collection space and document space, respectively
8-11:Thus, the result applies to term occurrence and document containment in a collection, and it applies to term occurrence and position containment in a document
8-12:This theoretical framework is useful for understanding and deciding the parameter estimation and combination in probabilistic retrieval models
8-13:The links between indepence based noise as document frequency, probabilistic interpretation of idf , information theory and Poisson described in this paper may lead to variable probabilistic idf and tf definitions and combinations as required in advanced and personalised information retrieval systems
